Scatter Markers¶

In [3]:
from bokeh.plotting import figure, output_file, show
from bokeh.io import output_notebook

# Prepare some data
x = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]
y = [6, 7, 2, 4, 5]

# Tell bokeh where to generate output
output_notebook()

# Call figure() 
p = figure(plot_width=400, plot_height=400)

# Add renderers
p.circle(x, y, size=20, color='navy', alpha=0.5)

# Ask Bokeh to show() or save() the results
show(p)

Hex Tiles¶

In [35]:
from bokeh.plotting import figure, output_file, show
from bokeh.io import output_notebook
from bokeh.util.hex import axial_to_cartesian

# Prepare some data
q = np.array([0, 0, 0, -1, -1, 1, 1])
r = np.array([0, -1, 1, 0, 1, -1, 0])
x, y = axial_to_cartesian(q, r, 1, 'pointytop')

# Tell bokeh where to generate output
output_notebook()

# Call figure() 
p = figure(plot_width=400, plot_height=400, toolbar_location=None)
p.grid.visible = False

# Add renderers
p.hex_tile(q, r, size=1, fill_color=['firebrick']*3 + ['navy']*4, line_color='white', alpha=0.5)
p.text(x, y, text=['(%d, %d)' % (q, r) for (q, r) in zip(q, r)], text_baseline='middle', text_align='center')

# Ask Bokeh to show() or save() the results
show(p)
Loading BokehJS ...
In [37]:
from bokeh.plotting import figure, output_file, show
from bokeh.io import output_notebook
from bokeh.util.hex import hexbin
from bokeh.transform import linear_cmap
import numpy as np

# Prepare some data
n = 50000
x = np.random.standard_normal(n)
y = np.random.standard_normal(n)

bins = hexbin(x, y, 0.1)

# Tell bokeh where to generate output
output_notebook()

# Call figure() 
p = figure(tools='wheel_zoom, reset', match_aspect=True, background_fill_color='#440154')
p.grid.visible = False

# Add renderers
p.hex_tile(q='q', r='r', size=0.1, line_color=None, source=bins, fill_color=linear_cmap('counts', 'Viridis256', 0, max(bins.counts)))

# Ask Bokeh to show() or save() the results
show(p)
Loading BokehJS ...

hole2 = {'x': [1.8, 1.8, 1.6], 'y': [3.4, 3.8, 3.8]}
polygon2 = {'x': [3, 4, 3], 'y': [1, 1, 3]}
polygon3 = {'x': [1, 2, 2, 1], 'y': [1, 1, 2, 2]}

    xs=[
        [[polygon1['x'], hole1['x'], hole2['x']]], 
        [[polygon2['x']]],
        [[polygon3['x'], hole3['x']]]
    ],

Images¶

In [4]:
from __future__ import division
from bokeh.plotting import figure, show
from bokeh.io import output_notebook
import numpy as np

# Prepare some data
N=20
img = np.empty((N, N), dtype=np.uint32)
view = img.view(dtype=np.uint8).reshape((N, N, 4))
for i in range(N):
    for j in range(N):
        view[i, j, 0] = int(255 * i / N)
        view[i, j, 1] = 158
        view[i, j, 2] = int(255 * j / N)
        view[i, j, 3] = 255

# Tell bokeh where to generate output
output_notebook()

# Call figure() 
p = figure(plot_width=400, plot_height=400, x_range=(0, 10), y_range=(0, 10))

# Add renderers
p.image_rgba(image=[img], x=[0], y=[0], dw=[10], dh=[10])

# Ask Bokeh to show() or save() the results
show(p)

import pandas as pd
from bokeh.plotting import figure, show
from bokeh.io import output_notebook
from bokeh.sampledata.stocks import AAPL

# Prepare some data
df = pd.DataFrame(AAPL)
df['date'] = pd.to_datetime(df['date'])

# Tell bokeh where to generate output
output_notebook()

# Call figure() 
p = figure(plot_width=800, plot_height=250, x_axis_type='datetime')

# Add renderers
p.line(df['date'], df['close'], color='navy', alpha=0.5)

# Ask Bokeh to show() or save() the results
show(p)

from bokeh.plotting import figure, show
from bokeh.io import output_notebook

# Prepare some data
x = [0.1, 0.5, 1.0, 1.5, 2.0, 2.5, 3.0]
y = [10**xx for xx in x]

# Tell bokeh where to generate output
output_notebook()

# Call figure() 
p = figure(plot_width=400, plot_height=400, y_axis_type='log')

# Add renderers
p.line(x, y, line_width=2)
p.circle(x, y, fill_color='white', size=8)

# Ask Bokeh to show() or save() the results
show(p)
